The Ledger Houses regard the Scorching Sands with professional
respect. That superheated dune-sea produced something Mafdet's own
institutions descend from: fraud-resistant verification.

The kiln houses of the Salt Ledger Kingdoms fired sun-baked
verification clay that changed color irreversibly when tampered
with. Our senior Ledger Clerks study recovered kiln-house seals
the way shipwrights study old hull designs -- not as curiosities,
but as ancestral technology. The principle is identical to our
Dual-Attestation Protocol: a document that cannot be altered
without visible evidence is the foundation of honest commerce.

The Burn Ledger -- the semi-buried audit complex recording kiln
batches, water allotments, and passage fees in one archive -- is the
closest inland equivalent to our Ledger House system. One building.
Multiple verification streams. Cross-referenced records. The Sands
solved the same problem we solve daily: how do you certify cargo
when the carrier has every incentive to lie?

The Scorch Clause still echoes in our maritime contracts.
Supplemental allocation for cargo in transit, mandatory material
certification, liability segmented by route -- these are not
abstractions to us. They are operating procedures. When our
Shoreward Assessors convert inland contracts to maritime law, the
Scorch Clause's structure is visible in every conversion table.

The Ember Wardens maintaining shade stations under the credo
"No crossing without measure" are kin to our Harbor Wardens in
spirit. Measurement before movement. Attestation before passage.
The language differs. The principle is the same.

The Ashbound Reavers exploiting water-discipline breakdowns
disrupt our supply chain. The Sand-Sea Carters' Guild factors
Reaver loss into corridor pricing -- a practical tax on the Sands'
lawlessness that raises costs at our docks.

The Cauterist Synod branding false seals as heresy perverts the
verification principle. The Shrine of the First Claw demands swift
justice for oath-breakers, but justice requires a living authority
accountable for the verdict. Fire is not an authority. Fire does
not sign its name.

The Sands remind us where our systems came from. The kiln houses
fired the first tamper-proof seals. The Burn Ledger kept the first
integrated manifests. We inherited their rigor. We must not
inherit their collapse.

